# Who can do what

Every inode has an **owner**, a **group**, and permissions for three classes.

## Three classes — who's asking?

- **user (u)** — the owner
- **group (g)** — members of the file's group
- **other (o)** — everyone else

## Three actions — meaning shifts by target

| | on a **file** | on a **directory** |
|---|---|---|
| **r** | view contents | list names (`ls`) |
| **w** | change contents | add / delete / rename inside |
| **x** | run it | **enter** it (`cd`), reach files within |

⚠️ **x on a directory = traversable.** Read-but-not-execute is locked — no `cd`, no access inside. And deleting a file is *writing its directory* — you can delete a file you can't write, if you can write its parent.

## Nine bits

```
   [ r w x ] [ r w x ] [ r w x ]
     owner     group     other
```

Read them with `ls -l`, change them with `chmod`.
